OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F313A1772010305
OL,3,CCan MPs criticise the Royal Family in
OL,4,Cthe House of Commons?
OL,6,FWhich, upon first reading, appears to
OL,7,Frule out any form of criticism of King
OL,8,FCharles, Prince William, Queen
OL,9,FCamilla, the Princess of Wales,
OL,10,FPrincess Anne, and all the others.
OL,12,FBut this is a misinterpretation,
OL,13,Faccording to the Speaker of the House
OL,14,Fof Commons, Sir Lindsay Hoyle.
OL,16,FHis office has set out clearly that
OL,17,Fthere is no "general prohibition" on
OL,18,Fdiscussing matters related to the
OL,19,Fmonarchy.
OL,26,@yD@MOUyD@aO]
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G3/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,314,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31304
SC,0004
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F313A1772010305
OL,3,CCan MPs criticise the Royal Family in
OL,4,Cthe House of Commons?
OL,6,FIt points to how MPs and Lords debated
OL,7,Fthe issues raised by the Sovereign
OL,8,FGrant Act in 2011 and the Counsellors
OL,9,Fof State Act in 2022.
OL,11,FHowever, there can be no "incidental
OL,12,Fcriticism" of senior working royals.
OL,14,FIn order for there to be criticism of
OL,15,Fthe Royal Family, there has to be a
OL,16,F"substantive motion" ` one that calls
OL,17,Ffor action or expresses an opinion.
OL,26,@sD@ZOUtD@JO]xD@AOUxD@TO]
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G4/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
